Dried Orange Slices:
	◦	Preheat oven to lowest temperature, I did 150 degrees F. 
	◦	Cut orange slices around ¼” thick
	◦	This step is key! Put the slices on wire cookie racks to bake! If you put them on just a baking sheet- they stick and won’t dry as evenly. I put the cookie rack on a baking sheet. 
	◦	Bake them around 4-6 hours. If doing multiple racks at once move them around at the 2 hour mark. 
	◦	At hour 4 check on them every 30 minutes until they are done when no stickiness remains and then remove from oven.
	◦	Once cool attach metal ornament hooks and hang from trees, garland or anywhere you’d like. 

Notes:
Smaller slices and less juicy oranges will dry the fastest.

Mr. Klein. He’s the boy where if your ice cream cone fell on the sidewalk he would give you his. First to give a hug and still learning that you don’t need to kiss everyone you meet goodbye. Still loves buffalos and bulls and now yaks are also on the list. His newest fascination is with zombies. He asked for hot dog pajamas for christmas (has never even eaten a hot dog). He tells me maple syrup is from a tree’s blood. He’s constantly analyzing if a creature we see has a skeleton or exoskeleton. Asked me this morning when we are going to go fishing. Randomly will say, “I love you, mommy” and “Dad! Put ON your glasses!” He’s the most curious human and exudes optimism. We are so lucky to do life with him. 🫶🏼⭐️🤍

Hours outside, simple pleasures of an unfussy life and lots of soulful connection between past and present.

For those who reach us on this tiny space of internet I hope it means you believe YOU CAN HAVE what you want. Whatever that means to you. Your life, your rules. 1. Find a honest, knowledgeable contractor that is excited about your dreams and the project. (I feel this is true for perhaps any place or project!) We found ours through our house manager here, if we hadn’t we also turn to Facebook groups in the area for references and start our digging and research from there. 

2. Live your life for you and your dreams. Your heart and your highest and best > opinions of others. (There are always people who will tell you can’t or shouldn’t move/renovate in another country.) 

3. Know you’ll find items locally that will sing to you and be “your style.” You’re buying local (which I think we all know is wonderful to support anywhere) and you’ll connect with those fellow creatives and you’ll be adding a layer of soulfulness to the home, that in our opinion, can’t be created any other way.

4. Mentally prepare yourself that things you’d never think of will most likely happen. I like to think of it as an opportunity to go with the flow and see what unfolds- so far everything has worked out better than I imagined even if it was a big road block when it happened. 

5. I’ve been telling my daughter this lately and honestly I wish I was telling it to myself over this whole process- listen to your inner brave voice. ✨

Growing up I had afternoons to myself and after homework I would watch movies and television shows that I didn’t think could be real. People could actually go outside and cut off a large branch from nature to enjoy in their home?! Wreaths and garland could be made from a branch here and there foraged from some trusty evergreen trees? It seemed so foreign and strange to me. I understand now I grew up in a desert climate and happened to not have those things readily available to me (I’m sure many people do where I’m from- I just happened not too.) 

I didn’t realize there could be trees (and so much green!) until I came to New England for the first time. I instantly fell in love. 

I’ve said it before and I’ll say it again. We found the nature that we love. That makes our heart sing. That brings joy to our souls. And I hope you’ve found yours, too. 

Sending you love. 💚

#historichomes #newengland

After years of dreaming, so much work, and a full renovation, bienvenidos to Casa Pantera! Located in the heart of the downtown of the alluring and vibrant city of Mérida, Mexico- a soulful, chic boutique stay for the avant garde sophisticate. 💫 NOW OPEN!

We first discovered our love for the Yucatán in 2017 during a spontaneous road trip from Tulum (thank you @dereknklein ) into the heart of the peninsula. We had never felt such p u r i t y. 

I mean purity in authenticity. In a high vibration and in LOVE. It felt like an energetic hug from the universe. It told us, “You are the creator of your life. Be you- it’s who you’re meant to be.”

The city of Mèrida is full of life, culture, and depth. It’s the capitol of the Mexican state of Yucatán and has rich and ancient Mayan history. Named the safest large city in Mexico, and the 5th in the world, It is a walkable historic centro filled with beautiful architecture, cuisine, and arts. 

You can dance the night away with the locals in the town squares, take a visit to the beach, explore the pueblos and cenotes (underwater caves) that dot the jungle around or explore the ancient ruins of the Mayans. Whatever you decide to do when you visit enjoy being immersed with the soul of this city. And once again welcome to CASA PANTERA. 
@casapanteramerida 

It’s now time we share it with those that want to venture to this magical city. We hope that it gives you feelings of wonder, expansion to live the life of your dreams in whatever 
way that means to YOU. Thank you for all your support and love throughout this journey. We feel incredibly lucky for this beautiful slice of the internet.

Here’s the unedited, honest review: 

“The design of this property is nothing short of breathtaking. Every detail has been meticulously curated to create an ambiance of elegance and sophistication. The chic finishes, from rustic wood to glossy ceramic tile floors, exude a sense of luxury and refinement. The use of monochrome aesthetics adds a touch of modernity, with a seamless blend of cream, white, surprising splashes of color that create a timeless and stylish atmosphere.
One of the standout features of this property is the carved panther head fountains. These whimsical and unexpected touches add a playful and imaginative aspect to the overall design. As water gently cascades from the panther heads, the fountains become captive focal points that evoke a sense of intrigue and charm.”

Previously almost every moment spent here in Mérida was packed with research, appointments, pickups, and showrooms. And now for the first time here our days are leisurely and slow. 

We dreamed of what these days would feel like. How we and others would experience their time here. We used that vision to develop the filter of how and what became the final details and decisions of Casa Pantera. Every selection fed the growing narrative of this home: A place to feel tranquility amid a busy, bustling, vibrant city. A backdrop to lifelong memories and once in a lifetime experiences. 

And now here I am- experiencing the end result of every selection and choice. And it’s everything I hoped it would be and more. And I hope if you ever choose to stay here- it’s everything and more for you, too.

Mexico Edition** I do my best editing after I can’t change it. 😆 

If you’re like me you’ll enjoy knowing that the only true drawers are the ones on the right of the range. The other “drawer look” cabinets hide our dishwasher and the cabinet that stores our hidden microwave and other large kitchen items like pots and pans.

Dove Hollow. 🕊️
The summer kitchen was built in 1791, and the front tavern completed in 1802. For more than 230 years this home has been here. Now is our time to love it so it can (hopefully) stand for 230 more. Since she was vacant for around 80 years, most of her original grandeur is still here- the hand cut moldings, original king pine floors, beehive ovens, stone hearths, and more. 

What a gift it is to be here. 
Living in New England was our dream. 
Antique homes have always held our hearts. 
This is the life I dreamed off. 

From the wavy panes of window glass to the ware of the painted floor…

From my personal dream of a formal dining room to a fireplace in most every room… 

We are here. We did it. A dream that could not have been realized without what we learned and gained from our first boutique stay @houseonthecape. All I can do is share my own personal journey. My own personal wisdom. Why I did things the way I have and how I continue to grow and change. What works. What doesn’t. Why, i feel, that is the case. 

And that is why we are coming out very soon with our master class. Hours and hours of information on both the business and design of boutique stays and more. All in hopes of cutting the learning curve and giving those who take it not only success in this venture, but also an opportunity to build wealth, financial freedom, and gain a deeper sense of connection to authenticity of self and utilizing that power within this field. 

All the knowledge coming, very soon. 💫

Being the steward of an old home is not for every one, and that is okay.

Some feel the slopes in the floor and think, “history” while others think, “imperfection.”

Some say “too much work” and others say “preserving history.” 

I do think however that no matter what you love or what I do, that what matters most is a safe and happy home. 

Sending you love. 💫

If you’ve known me long enough you know I’ve always loved the ritual of special drink and serveware- I would often tell friends, “if you’re having a drink anyway why not out of a goblet?” 

It is one of the tiny ways that makes my everyday feel special to me (#selfcare) and how I hope to create special moments for my children that will become part of the fabric of their childhood memories. 

I set this table with the beautiful and durable @juliskaofficial outdoor line. I wanted pieces that I was proud to entertain with as well as not worry about the children running outside with them. A plate or goblet that could tumble from a tabletop and survive or jumble in our picnic basket on the walk up to the meadow and be just as beautiful as when I placed it in. This picnic blanket is as pretty on the table as it is to live on and wrap up in, and especially just as easy to wash. I know it will be the foundation of many, many summer memories to come.

Thank you @juliskaofficial for these beautiful pieces. We love the timelessness and craftsmanship they represent and look forward to the visual stories that we will tell with them over and over again. 

Wishing you a beautiful and special summertime. 🍓

Along with the pieces of history we gather, we also own some artifacts that are so special to us. 

The original family Bible of the family who built the home- listing the births, marriages and deaths in the family. 

An oil painting of the original owner, Abner, which is hung in the dining room. 

A hand painted water color family registry from one of Abner’s sons which hangs in our parlor. 

Old handwritten receipts ordering ale for the tavern. 

And perhaps my personal favorite- we have some wall graffiti in the attic bedroom from 1836.

Some of these were special in their original time, some not. But now they are all a part of the history- and that is what I will treasure.

Here are the reasons why we moved our family across the country to buy an historic 221 year old home. 

It was always our dream. From early on in our relationship (age 16!) Chase and I have always had a deep love for old homes. Being from Utah there aren’t many historic homes before 1900. This is a beautiful chapter for us having this 1802 tavern. This home means so much to our family. 

Freedom for my children to roam. 8 acres for my kids to climb trees, run in pastures, and explore the woods that mean so much to us. 

I wished for this and it’s happening and I’m so grateful.  And I hope all your dreams are coming to fruition too.

Meet our 5 month old identical twin Babydoll Southdown sheep:🐑🐑

🎀Goldie and Olive 🎀

Our home came with many a story of its past. One of them is that the original builder of the tavern we now call home also utilized his property as a sheep farm in the 1800s; the small well house out back even being equipped with a small wood stove to keep winter lambs warm. 🤍

A true bonded pair, the girls only make a peep when they can’t see the other. Goldie so far is curious and brave and Olive is shy and sweet and still a bit skeptical of everything around her. 

We chose Babydoll sheep for their small size, temperament, gentleness, and the way their adorable faces make our hearts burst!

Hampton has taken a special stewardship of them, rising early everyday since they came home with us last week, and whispering to us if she can go feed them. That first morning, (the first early rising) after bringing the girls home Hampton told me at breakfast, “Mom, I promised Olive last night that I will always feed her before I feed myself. And I am going to feed them every day so that the girls will know me.” 

We are all so in love and we hope their faces here will bring you as much joy as they have already given us! ✨

#southdowns #newengland

Time and time again we are asked this question… 

Is it haunted?! 

As many of you know our home was a tavern and inn in the early 1800s. 

Our home was nestled on the main route for travelers to and from Providence, Rhode Island and New York City. As you can image we have had many, many humans within these walls as travelers would would eat, drink, and sleep here. This tavern also employed up to 14 people during any given timeframe. 

With so much human energy being here it seems likely to me that some of that energy may be residual, that it may come and go. 

The truth is is that have have never felt or seen anything out of the ordinary. Chase, our son Klein, and two of our guests who have stayed with us- have. Nothing scary. 

Being a steward of an old home comes with many different responsibilities and one of those for some is to share their space with the unknown. 🕯️

Any other old home owners have haunted houses?!

Our Annual Vermont Travel Itinerary. 🍁🍂🥮

We have been doing a Vermont road trip for the last 8 years in October. It’s one of my absolute very favorite things we do each year!!

We do the same things, eat at the same places, and drive the same drives. It’s a tradition that I hope to carry even as the kids are adults and possibly have their own families. 

Things to do: (heading north from Connecticut) 

	◦	Stop in Woodstock- visit Farmhouse pottery, walk the downtown, we always get food from a grocery store and picnic 
	◦	Sugarbush Farm (get your maple flavored souvenirs from here!) The head up to Stowe. 
	◦	Cold Hollow Cider Mill (the BEST donuts!) 
	◦	Gondola at Stowe 
	◦	Smuggler’s Notch State Park 
	◦	Explore Main Street in Stowe
	◦	Middle Covered Bridge in Woodstock
	◦	Apple picking at Scott Farm (also they have wine and cider tastings here)

When to go:
This is the golden question! Each year the leaves peak at different times. If you go the first 10 days of October you should be golden (Really 2 weeks is good but I’m a Virgo so it’s 10 days for me.) We honestly don’t mind if it’s a bit pre or post peak since it beautiful either way. 

When to book:
We always book our places to stay in July since if you wait too long the great places will usually fully be booked by September! Also prices get more expensive the closer you get- cancellations do happen though! 

And just for us we now always visit our friend @nicholeleevt who is an amazing yoga instructor and has the most dreamy farmhouse! 🤍🍂

Save this for later and we will share more when we head up this year. Vermont is pure magic in October!

As a young girl I loved books and movies that felt like they transported me to magical places. To me, the magic was in trees, the shades of bright green in sprawling pastures, autumnal hues in tall, tall trees and homes that felt they were from another time. 🌳 

At that time I didn’t grasp that those places could be real. That an everyday life could be lived in those magical places. Later in life (after my first trip to New England) the stories I read and visions I saw as a child became a tangible reality. 🐑 🐓 

Living here now I’m still struck by the majesty and beauty that expands over my every sense; from just a step outside my door.

I often say (and I think will always say) I found my nature. I needed to find the nature for me. 

And it’s my hope you’ve found the right nature for you. 🤍

“I’m so glad I live in a world where there are Octobers.” 
— Lucy Maud Montgomery, Ann of Green Gables.

Part 1 of our renovation plans in my best British accent. 😂😎

Let me know if you think we should keep the walls as is or paint them?

The upstairs (chapel area) of the church doesn’t have as many extensive renovations needed as the downstairs area. After the next few meeting with our architect, we will be able to share many more details.

We are going to be using the upstairs as a large living space/event space. We will be leveling out the floor as it was originally built. We will also be taking out the pews, restoring each window and giving the choir loft a facelift and making it into a library space with seating. We are also going to be adding an outdoor patio to the side of the church. 
Currently there are two stair cases up to the choir lift. One we will be keeping one and the other we will be converted into a powder bath. As far as other basic details- we will be adding a large fireplace, removing up the carpet and using the original pine wide plank floors and repurposing every piece of the pulpit. 

We have many more meetings with the city, building code department, and health department before being able to actual start the reno to this beautiful historic structure. However, like our other places we are putting all of our energy into honoring it’s history, but also bringing it back and giving this place new life! 💫

These historic places bring us so much joy and it is our honor to share many of these places with you both as boutique stays and here on our spot of the internet. 

There is magic to any home new, old, or in between however to me old homes are extra rewarding. Here are 3 things we’ve learned. 

	1.	Let the homes speak for themselves. 
They already have a history, a story. And it’s up to us how it’s told. We get to see how the sunlight reflects on doors and walls, the undertones in the wood and bricks. We observe and take in that information and let the colors, textures and nuances of a space form. We get to experience our lives as we go from room to room, feeling the movement of energy- telling us where to place a plush chair or blanket, a stack of books or piece of art. 

	2.	Be patient. 
This can mean many different things. Costs, repairs, maintenance etc but really it’s the patience in that it’s not all perfect, and that it’s truly not meant to be. 

	3.	Stewardship. 
Stewardship is intentional. It’s more than a sense of consideration about the future… It is honoring the past, enjoying the present, and doing what we can to preserve the future of these places. 

These homes hold our lives. They foster connection and hold the memories of family and friends. They allow our creativity to bloom and give us a deeper sense of purpose and joy. And I will be forever grateful for that.
